public Complex divide(Complex divisor) throws NullArgumentException {
    MathUtils.checkNotNull(divisor);
    if (isNaN || divisor.isNaN) {
        return NaN;
    }

    if (divisor.getReal() == 0.0 && divisor.getImaginary() == 0.0) {
        // Divisor is zero
        if (real == 0.0 && imaginary == 0.0) {
            return NaN;
        }
        return INF; // assuming INF is defined
    }

    if (divisor.isInfinite() && !isInfinite()) {
        return ZERO;
    }

    final double c = divisor.getReal();
    final double d = divisor.getImaginary();

    if (FastMath.abs(c) < FastMath.abs(d)) {
        double q = c / d;
        double denominator = c * q + d;
        return createComplex((real * q + imaginary) / denominator,
            (imaginary * q - real) / denominator);
    } else {
        double q = d / c;
        double denominator = d * q + c;
        return createComplex((imaginary * q + real) / denominator,
            (imaginary - real * q) / denominator);
    }
}

But we need to consider isInfinite for numerator? If numerator is infinite, and divisor is zero, we should still return infinite? Actually, infinite/0 is still infinite. But the check for divisor.isInfinite() already handles divisor infinite. For divisor zero, we should not check isInfinite because it's not infinite. So we just return INF if numerator not zero (including infinite cases). So the fix above is fine.

